WEBVTT

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:28.850
Tom Davis: Alright everyone, thanks for joining. It's 10:02 AM, so let's get started. The main agenda for today is the Data Science team's presentation of the Q3 sales forecast.

00:00:29.150 --> 00:00:32.410
Tom Davis: Anya, the floor is yours.

00:00:33.050 --> 00:00:43.910
Dr. Anya Sharma: Thanks, Tom. Good morning, everyone. As Tom mentioned, Ben and I will walk you through our demand forecast for the upcoming quarter. We'll cover the overall business forecast, and then we have some high-level product category breakdowns.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.180
Dr. Anya Sharma: Let me just share my screen... okay, can everyone see the main dashboard?

00:00:50.010 --> 00:01:25.830
Dr. Anya Sharma: Great. So, at a high level, our model projects a total revenue of $82.5 million for Q3. This represents a 4.5% growth quarter-over-quarter and a 9% growth year-over-year. This forecast was generated using our updated Prophet model, which now incorporates promotional calendars and three key macroeconomic indicators we've found to have a strong correlation.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:36.950
Maria Rodriguez: Sorry to jump in so quickly, Anya, but $82.5 million feels... conservative. My regional managers are projecting closer to $85 million based on the pipeline strength, especially in the enterprise segment.

00:01:37.610 --> 00:01:50.110
Dr. Anya Sharma: That's a fair point, Maria. We did see the strong pipeline data. However, the model is weighting the recent slowdown in consumer spending, which is one of the macro indicators, a bit heavily. It's creating a dampening effect on the raw pipeline growth.

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:56.540
David Chen: And what's the confidence interval on that $82.5 million? Are we talking plus or minus one million, or five?

00:01:57.010 --> 00:02:08.310
Ben Carter: Hi David, Ben here. Our 95% confidence interval for the aggregate forecast is quite tight, it's between $80.5 million and $84.5 million. So, Maria's $85 million is just outside the upper bound of what the model considers likely.

00:02:08.990 --> 00:02:17.090
David Chen: A four-million-dollar range is significant for our financial planning. That's the difference between hitting our EPS target and missing it. How did this compare to last quarter's accuracy?

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:30.430
Dr. Anya Sharma: Last quarter, our forecast was off by 2.1%, so we landed squarely within the predicted interval. Our backtesting shows this new model has a Mean Absolute Percentage Error, or MAPE, of about 3.5% over the last two years, which is an improvement on the old SARIMA model.

00:02:31.210 --> 00:02:45.380
Maria Rodriguez: I appreciate the statistical rigor, I really do. But my concern is that the model is too reliant on historical data and these macro trends, and maybe not sensitive enough to the specific, high-value deals my team is actively working to close. These aren't just 'pipeline', these are deals with verbal commits.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:03:00.850
Sarah Jenkins: I have a different concern. Maria is worried about the top line, I'm worried about the details. Can this model tell me what this means for Product SKU 75B in the Northeast? We were completely stocked out for three weeks last year, and it was a disaster. The aggregate number doesn't help me prevent that.

00:03:01.410 --> 00:03:10.590
Dr. Anya Sharma: An excellent question, Sarah. The current presentation is at the category level, not SKU. Granular SKU-level forecasting is our next big project. It's exponentially more complex due to sparsity and intermittency.

00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:20.940
Dr. Anya Sharma: For now, we can provide a directional forecast for the category that SKU 75B belongs to, and then apply a historical SKU-mix percentage. It's not as accurate as a direct SKU forecast, but it's the best we can do with the current model.

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:31.020
Sarah Jenkins: Okay... that's... a start. But it feels like a big gamble. If the mix has shifted, we're either going to be holding useless inventory or stocking out again. Can we manually adjust the forecast for that specific SKU based on what we know?

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:41.220
Ben Carter: We could potentially do that. We can take the model's output for the category and allow for a manual override on the SKU-mix percentages. But that introduces a subjective layer, and it makes it harder to measure the model's pure performance over time.

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:50.530
David Chen: I'm with Sarah on this. A purely statistical model that causes a stock-out is a failure, no matter how low its MAPE is. We need to be able to blend the model's output with expert domain knowledge from people like Sarah and Maria.

00:03:51.110 --> 00:03:58.310
Tom Davis: Okay, this is a good discussion. Anya, Ben, what would it take to incorporate some of these manual adjustments or expert overrides into the final number that we use for planning?

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:11.770
Dr. Anya Sharma: We can definitely set up a process for that. Perhaps a two-stage review. Stage one is our purely model-driven forecast. Stage two is a review session with stakeholders like Maria and Sarah to apply their insights and create a consensus forecast. We just need to be diligent about tracking the 'before' and 'after' to keep refining the model.

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:20.190
Maria Rodriguez: I like that. A consensus forecast. If we can adjust the enterprise segment projection up slightly and formalize that adjustment, I'd feel much more comfortable using this to set my team's quotas.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:27.420
Sarah Jenkins: Same here. If I can put in a higher allocation for SKU 75B based on our early warning systems, I can place my procurement orders with more confidence.

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:36.450
David Chen: From a finance perspective, I'm okay with that, as long as we have a clear audit trail of why the numbers were changed. I need to be able to explain the variance between the 'pure' forecast and the 'consensus' forecast to the CFO.

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:44.970
Tom Davis: Excellent. It sounds like we have a path forward. So, action items: Anya, your team will continue with the model. But we'll add a consensus review meeting to the quarterly process. For this quarter, let's get that scheduled for early next week.

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:55.740
Dr. Anya Sharma: We can do that. We'll come prepared with the category-level breakdown and the historical SKU-mix percentages, Sarah. And Maria, we can run a simulation to see what impact a 5% higher close rate on enterprise deals would have on the total.

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:59.030
Maria Rodriguez: Perfect, that would be very helpful. Thank you.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:01.890
Sarah Jenkins: Appreciate it, Anya. Looking forward to it.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:08.520
David Chen: Sounds good. Just make sure the final output for me includes the base model forecast, the consensus forecast, and a list of the adjustments made.

00:05:08.930 --> 00:05:12.710
Ben Carter: No problem, David. We can build that into our reporting dashboard.

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:17.480
Tom Davis: Great. Any other questions or points before we wrap up? We're at 44 minutes.

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:27.010
Dr. Anya Sharma: Just one final thought. As we get more granular, we'll need cleaner data, especially from the supply chain and sales ops side. Things like real-time promotional flags and more structured pipeline data will make a huge difference in accuracy.

00:05:27.650 --> 00:05:30.950
Maria Rodriguez: Point taken. I can work with my team on pipeline data hygiene.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:34.120
Sarah Jenkins: Same on our end for inventory and logistics data.

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:41.360
Tom Davis: Fantastic collaboration, everyone. Thanks for the productive discussion. We'll send out the invite for the consensus review meeting shortly. Have a great day.
